<para id="fs-id1164559105730">The muscles that change the shape of the lens in the eyes have become weak, causing vision problems for a person. In particular, the muscles cannot pull hard enough on the edges of the lens to make it less convex.</para>
<para id="fs-id1164564824392">Part A—What condition does inability cause?</para>
<para id="fs-id1164563142216">Part B—Where are images focused with respect to the retina?</para>
<para id="fs-id1164563559905">Part C—Which type of lens corrects this person’s problem? Explain.</para>
<list id="fs-id1164562217884" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>Part A—This condition causes hyperopia.<newline/>
Part B—Images are focused between the lens and the retina.<newline/>
Part C—A converging lens gathers the rays slightly so they focus onto the retina.</item>
<item>Part A—This condition causes myopia.<newline/>
Part B—Images are focused between the lens and the retina.<newline/>
Part C—A converging lens gathers the rays slightly so they focus onto the retina.</item>
<item>Part A—This condition causes hyperopia.<newline/>
Part B—Images are focused between the lens and the retina.<newline/>
Part C—A diverging lens spreads the rays slightly so they focus onto the retina.</item>
<item>Part A—This condition causes myopia.<newline/>
Part B—Images are focused between the lens and the retina.<newline/>
Part C—A diverging lens spreads the rays slightly so they focus onto the retina.</item>
</list>
